Normalization
🧠 What is Normalization?
👉 Normalization = remove duplicate data + organize tables
Goal:
No data repetition
Better structure
Easy updates

🧠 Simple Example (Before Normalization ❌)
Table: students
id	name	course	 instructor
1	Rahul	AWS	 John
2	Amit	Linux	 Mike
3	Neha	AWS	 John
👉 Problem:
“AWS + John” repeated 😓
Waste of space
Hard to update

✅ After Normalization
Table 1: students
id	name	  course_id
1	Rahul	    1
2	Amit.     2
3	Neha	    1

Table 2: courses
course_id	course 	instructor
1	             AWS	            John
2	             Linux	            Mike

👉 Now:
No repetition
Clean structure
Easy updates

📘 Types of Normalization (Important Levels)
1 First Normal Form (1NF)
👉 Rule:
No multiple values in one column
Each field = single value

❌ Wrong
name	courses
Rahul	AWS, Linux

✅ Correct
name	course
Rahul	AWS
Rahul	Linux

2 Second Normal Form (2NF)
👉 Rule:
Must be in 1NF
No partial dependency

🧠 Simple Meaning
👉 Every column should depend on full primary key

❌ Wrong
student_id	   course 	instructor
1	                AWS             John
👉 instructor depends only on course ❌

✅ Fix
Split into:
students table
courses table

3️⃣ Third Normal Form (3NF)
👉 Rule:
Must be in 2NF
No indirect dependency

🧠 Simple Meaning
👉 Column should depend only on primary key

❌ Wrong
student_id	course_id	instructor

👉 instructor depends on course_id ❌

✅ Fix
Move instructor to course table

🧠 Easy Way to Remember
1NF → No multi-values
2NF → No partial dependency
3NF → No indirect dependency

🔥 Real-Life Example
👉 E-commerce system:
Before: | order_id | customer | product | price |

After:
customers table
products table
orders table
👉 Clean + scalable system

⚖️ Advantages
✅ Less duplicate data
✅ Easy updates
✅ Better performance (in some cases)
✅ Data consistency

⚠️ Disadvantages
❌ Too many tables
❌ Complex JOINs
👉 That’s why sometimes we use denormalization
